{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"72dc57d5-8139-42d6-a522-83170893af83","content":"The project directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### In your `.csproj`, add these properties:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Required NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n\n  <!-- Must be a console app with stdio -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points:\n\n1. **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a dotnet tool\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`)\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — required for stdio transport\n\n### Build, pack, and publish:\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install and run it with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThe critical piece most people miss is **`PackAsTool`** — without it, `dotnet pack` produces a library package, not a tool package.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bd8875f0-f6ce-4614-a4ff-84ffe5ca93c0","outputTokens":466,"requestId":"AC04:188DB0:DC109E:1126CA4:6A012DA8"},"id":"78a6a625-094c-4771-b78d-d29ae1fdba9b","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:15:29.285Z","parentId":"01ea966b-9a5d-46f2-864f-f3ee6f1cec34"}
